<sn><md>### Behavior of Gases Entering an Atmospheric Zone{.fg-red .text-center}

Consider an atmospheric zone located **10 km above the ground**, where the ambient temperature is **10┬░C**. Three different air masses (gases) with varying temperatures approach this zone:

* **A = 10┬░C**
* **B = 5┬░C**
* **C = 15┬░C**

![diagram-before](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES%202nd%20Year/Atmospheric%20Chemistry/atmosphere-gas-movement-diagram-1-bef.svg)


We can analyze their behavior step by step based on temperature differences and density effects.

---

#### 1. Air Mass A (10┬░C){.text-center}

* The temperature of air mass A is **equal** to the atmospheric zone (10┬░C).
* This means air A is in ==thermal equilibrium== with the zone.

**Result:**

* Air A **will neither rise nor sink**.
* It remains ==stable== in its position.

---

#### 2. Air Mass B (5┬░C){.text-center}

* Air B is **colder** than the zone (10┬░C).
* Cold air is ==denser and heavier== than the surrounding warmer air.

**Result:**

* Air B ==will sink downward== due to its higher density.
* Stability: **Stable**, as the colder air will not rise spontaneously.

---

#### 3. Air Mass C (15┬░C){.text-center}

* Air C is **warmer** than the zone (10┬░C).
* Warm air is less dense and ==tends to rise==.

**Result:**

* Air C ==will rise upward== into higher layers.
* Stability: `Unstable`, as the warmer air will mix with the surrounding cooler air.

---


![diagram-after](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES%202nd%20Year/Atmospheric%20Chemistry/atmosphere-gases-movement-diagram-after.svg)

