- **When air descends**:  
  - Pressure increases тЖТ Air compresses тЖТ Gains energy тЖТ **Heats up**.  

**Key Point**: No heat is added or lost externallyтАФonly **pressure change** drives the temperature change.  

---

### **Simple Example**:  
Imagine pumping a bicycle tire:  
- The pump compresses air тЖТ It heats up (**adiabatic heating**).  
- If you release air suddenly, it expands and cools (**adiabatic cooling**).  

This is why **rising air** (e.g., in thunderstorms) cools and forms clouds!  
</md></sn><sn><md>## Lapse Rate Concept{.text-center .fg-red}

Imagine two friends, Tamim and Hridoy, living in a 12-floor building. Tamim feels a **warmer temperature**, while Hridoy experiences a **cooler temperature**. This happens because the **ground releases heat after absorbing solar energy**, causing the air near the surface to be warmer. As air rises, its temperature gradually decreases, transitioning from warm to cold.

In the atmosphere, **temperature changes with altitude**. For each kilometer of ascent, there is a measurable **temperature difference**. Even at the same height, different types of gases can experience **different rates of temperature change** depending on their physical properties and composition.

